{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14064"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14064"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.14,0.06,0.52,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6723"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6155"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43472"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department, having been retrieved from the scene of a motor vehicle crash. He was the front seat passenger in a head-on collision. He is able to give full details and his only complaint is of severe pain in his left knee after it hit the dashboard. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 124/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The only abnormal finding is an obvious deformity of his left knee, which is then X-rayed (Image ). Shortly after this, it is noted that his dorsalis pedis pulse is diminished on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact orthopaedic team","Contact vascular surgery team","Limb immobilisation","Closed reduction","Angiography"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a posterior knee dislocation following a high-impact \u0027dashboard\u0027 injury in a motor vehicle crash. The diminished dorsalis pedis pulse indicates potential vascular compromise, which requires immediate action. In this scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed reduction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Prompt reduction of the dislocation can restore blood flow and prevent further neurovascular damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContacting the orthopaedic team\u003C/strong\u003E is important, but it should not delay the urgent reduction. The orthopaedic team should be notified immediately after the reduction is performed or if the reduction is unsuccessful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContacting the vascular surgery team\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if vascular compromise persists after reduction, but it is not the immediate next step. The priority is to attempt to restore blood flow through reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimb immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient in this case. While immobilisation is important to prevent further injury, it does not address the urgent need to restore blood flow to the limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiography\u003C/strong\u003E can be valuable in assessing vascular injury, but it is not the immediate next step. Delaying reduction to perform angiography could lead to irreversible ischemic damage. Angiography may be considered after reduction if vascular compromise persists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter closed reduction, immediate reassessment of the neurovascular status is crucial. If pulses do not return or there are other signs of persistent vascular compromise, urgent vascular surgery consultation and possible angiography would then be indicated. Orthopaedic consultation for definitive management and assessment of associated ligamentous injuries is also essential following reduction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Posterior knee dislocation requires urgent closed reduction, especially if there are signs of vascular compromise.","Vascular assessment is crucial in knee injuries, as popliteal artery injury can occur in up to 40% of knee dislocations.","After reduction, reassessment of neurovascular status and urgent orthopaedic consultation are essential next steps."],"references":["Gottlieb M, Koyfman A, Long B. Evaluation and Management of Knee Dislocation in the Emergency Department. J Emerg Med. 2020; 58:34-42"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14064"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21446"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21446"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w3RNRpl5DgiQadY7nLuZ6W6pUf9URh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w3RNRpl5DgiQadY7nLuZ6W6pUf9URh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":7